The author of the Philopatris perpetually treats the Christians as a company of dreaming enthusiasts , c . 
and in one place he manifestly alludes to the vision in which St . 
Paul was transported to the third heaven . 
In another place , Triephon , who personates a Christian , after deriding the gods of Paganism , proposes a mysterious oath . 
The Pagan multitude , reserving their gratitude for temporal benefits alone , rejected the inestimable present of life and immortality , which was offered to mankind by Jesus of Nazareth . 
In the first and second books of Origen , Celsus treats the birth and character of our Savior with the most impious contempt . 
The orator Libanius praises Porphyry and Julian for confuting the folly of a sect . 
