is not pleased with so positive an exclusion of any former martyr of the episcopal rank . 
G. It was in the choice of Cyprian , either to die a martyr , or to live an apostate but on the choice depended the alternative of honor or infamy . 
The assurance of a lasting reputation upon earth , a motive so congenial to the vanity of human nature , often served to animate the courage of the martyrs . 
The annual commemoration of their virtues and sufferings was observed as a sacred ceremony , and at length terminated in religious worship . 
had been dismissed from the tribunal or the prisons of the Pagan magistrates , obtained such honors as were justly due to their imperfect martyrdom and their generous resolution . 
The most pious females courted the permission of imprinting kisses on the fetters which they had worn , and on the wounds which they had received . 
Distinctions like these , whilst they display the exalted merit , betray the inconsiderable number of those who suffered , and of those who died , for the profession of Christianity . 
Whatever opinion we may entertain of the character or principles of Thomas Becket , we must acknowledge that he suffered death with a constancy not unworthy of the primitive martyrs . 
