The mind of Diocletian himself was less adapted indeed to speculative inquiries , than to the active labors of war and government . 
The bishops held an honorable rank in their respective provinces , and were treated with distinction and respect , not only by the people , but by the magistrates themselves . 
Prosperity had relaxed the nerves of discipline . 
Fraud , envy , and malice prevailed in every congregation . 
The presbyters aspired to the episcopal office , which every day became an object more worthy of their ambition . 
