His fears were soon alarmed by the view of a danger from which he very narrowly escaped . 
Jealousy and resentment prevailed in every breast , but especially in that of Diocletian . 
A great number of persons , distinguished either by the offices which they had filled , or by the favor which they had enjoyed , were thrown into prison . 
Every mode of torture was put in practice , and the court , as well as city , was polluted with many bloody executions . 
The ecclesiastical historians , from whom alone we derive a partial and imperfect knowledge of this persecution , are at a loss how to account for the fears and dangers of the emperors . 
