of Eusebius for the description and for the scenes of these tortures . 
He closes his narration by assuring us that these were the martyrdoms inflicted in Palestine , during the whole course of the persecution . 
But when he proceeds to mention his own journey into Egypt , his language insensibly becomes more cautious and moderate . 
Having thus provided a secure evasion , he commits the equivocal passage to his readers and translators justly conceiving that their piety would induce them to prefer the most favorable sense . 
