imputes to Constantine the death of two wives , of the innocent Fausta , and of an adulteress , who was the mother of his three successors . 
According to Jerom , three or four years elapsed between the death of Crispus and that of Fausta . 
The elder Victor is prudently silent . 
If Fausta was put to death , it is reasonable to believe that the private apartments of the palace were the scene of her execution . 
The orator Chrysostom indulges his fancy by exposing the naked desert mountain to be devoured by wild beasts . 
He seems to call her the mother of Crispus . 
She might assume that title by adoption . 
At least , she was not considered as his mortal enemy . 
Julian compares the fortune of Fausta with that of Parysatis , the Persian queen . 
