M. During the long period of the reign of Constantius , the provinces of the East were afflicted by the calamities of the Persian war . 
The event of the day was most commonly adverse to the Romans , but in the battle of Singara , heir imprudent valor had almost achieved a signal and decisive victory . 
But the prudent Sapor had watched the moment of victory . 
The sincerity of history declares , that the Romans were vanquished with a dreadful slaughter , and that the flying remnant of the legions was exposed to the most intolerable hardships . 
The son of Sapor , the heir of his crown , had been made a captive in the Persian camp . 
The unhappy youth , who might have excited the compassion of the most savage enemy , was scourged , tortured , and publicly executed by the inhuman Romans . 
published the Itineraries of Alexander and Trajan , in order to direct the victorious Constantius in the footsteps of those great conquerors of the East . 
gives a lively description of the wandering and predatory life of the Saracens , who stretched from the confines of Assyria to the cataracts of the Nile . 
It appears from the adventures of Malchus , which Jerom has related in so entertaining a manner , that the high road between Beraea and Edessa was infested by these robbers . 
We shall take from Eutropius the general idea of the war . 
