This large and populous city was situate about two days' journey from the Tigris , in the midst of a pleasant and fertile plain at the foot of Mount Masius . 
A treble enclosure of brick walls was defended by a deep ditch and the intrepid resistance of Count Lucilianus , and his garrison , was seconded by the desperate courage of the people . 
By the labor of the Persians , the course of the river was stopped below the town , and the waters were confined on every side by solid mounds of earth . 
The Persians were instantly driven to the assault , and the fate of Nisibis depended on the event of the day . 
The elephants , made furious by their wounds , increased the disorder , and trampled down thousands of the Persian archers . 
