Even in his sleep , the mind of the Caesar must have been agitated by the hopes and fears of his fortune . 
This epistle is inscribed with the modest appellation of Caesar but Julian solicits in a peremptory , though respectful , manner , the confirmation of the title of Augustus . 
He acknowledges the irregularity of his own election , while he justifies , in some measure , the resentment and violence of the troops which had extorted his reluctant consent . 
But he reserves for himself the nomination of his other civil and military officers , with the troops , the revenue , and the sovereignty of the provinces beyond the Alps . 
In this negotiation Julian claimed no more than he already possessed . 
The delegated authority which he had long exercised over the provinces of Gaul , Spain , and Britain , was still obeyed under a name more independent and august . 
The soldiers and the people rejoiced in a revolution which was not stained even with the blood of the guilty . 
