M. Chapter XXIII Reign Of Julian . 
The restoration of the Jewish temple was secretly connected with the ruin of the Christian church . 
Julian still continued to maintain the freedom of religious worship , without distinguishing whether this universal toleration proceeded from his justice or his clemency . 
As he was sensible that the Christians gloried in the name of their Redeemer , he countenanced , and perhaps enjoined , the use of the less honorable appellation of Galilaeans . 
Such of these regulations as appeared necessary to check the ambition and avarice of the ecclesiastics , were soon afterwards imitated by the wisdom of an orthodox prince . 
The peculiar distinctions which policy has bestowed , or superstition has lavished , on the sacerdotal order , must be confined to those priests who profess the religion of the state . 
And this law was confirmed by the invariable practice of Julian himself . 
