Arsaces Tiranus , or Diran , had ceased to reign twenty five years before , in . 
The intermediate changes in Armenia , and the character of this Arsaces , the son of Diran , are traced by M. St . 
Martin , at considerable length , in his supplement to Le Beau , ii . 
As long as his Grecian queen Olympias maintained her influence , Arsaces was faithful to the Roman and Christian alliance . 
The patriarch Narses retired from the impious court to a safe seclusion . 
Yet Pharandsem was equally hostile to the Persian influence , and Arsaces began to support with vigor the cause of Julian . 
