yet he allows that the sophist or magician , the guilty favorite of Julian , and the personal enemy of Valentinian , was dismissed on the payment of a small fine . 
Ipae supra impacati Rhen semibarbaras ripas raptim vexilla constituens Princeps creatus ad difficilem militiam revertisti . 
M. Ammianus says , in general terms , subagrestis ingenii , nec bellicis nec liberalibus studiis eruditus . 
The orator Themistius , with the genuine impertinence of a Greek , wishes for the first time to speak the Latin language , the dialect of his sovereign . 
His presence of mind procured him a longer respite , and a more splendid fate . 
At first he lurked in the villages of Bithynia , continually changing his habitation and his disguise . 
The body of the people was infected with a spirit of discontent they regretted the justice and the abilities of Sallust , who had been imprudently dismissed from the praefecture of the East . 
They despised the character of Valens , which was rude without vigor , and feeble without mildness . 
The circumstances were propitious to the designs of a usurper . 
The soldiers , who were prepared for his reception , saluted their trembling prince with shouts of joy and vows of fidelity . 
The usurper improved this unexpected success with some degree of courage and dexterity . 
He artfully propagated the rumors and opinions the most favorable to his interest while he deluded the populace by giving audience to the frequent , but imaginary , ambassadors of distant nations . 
His generals passed the Bosphorus , and subdued , without an effort , the unarmed , but wealthy provinces of Bithynia and Asia . 
The alliance of Faustina , the widow of the emperor Constantius , who intrusted herself and her daughter to the hands of the usurper , added dignity and reputation to his cause . 
The princess Constantia , who was then about five years of age , accompanied , in a litter , the march of the army . 
